column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18402_ShortDesc", "Flower of deepest blue hues")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18402_LongDesc", "This particular flower is only found in the colder regions of Hyboria. Its deep blue hues, taken from the moan-soaked night skies of winter, are coveted for the making of fine dyes.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18403_ShortDesc", "Bandages used for binding wounds")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18403_LongDesc", "<span style=\"italic\">\'She sat on a couch with her wounded leg extended upon it, and the Tecuhltli woman had just bound it with silk bandages. Valeria\'s red-stained sword lay on the couch beside her.\'</> - Red Nails\n\nWounds require special care, to heal and to avoid infection and putrefaction. Sometimes, upon the battlefield, all one can do is bind a wound with strips of fiber.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18500_ShortDesc", "Buzzing hive of honey-producing bees")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18500_LongDesc", "<span style=\"italic\">They ran full into a cloud of stinging death.</> - The Hour of the Dragon\n\nEven the most devolved of savages rarely fails to note the wiliness of beasts to endure countless stings in order to acquire that coveted, golden jelly of the bees. Humankind first learns to remember where wild hives grow and devise clever ways to acquire the treasure inside. As hunters become gatherers and gatherers turn to agriculture, humankind learns to propagate their own hives close to home.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18501_ShortDesc", "Buzzing hive of honey-producing bees")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18501_LongDesc", "<span style=\"italic\">They ran full into a cloud of stinging death.</> - The Hour of the Dragon\n\nEven the most devolved of savages rarely fails to note the wiliness of beasts to endure countless stings in order to acquire that coveted, golden jelly of the bees. Humankind first learns to remember where wild hives grow and devise clever ways to acquire the treasure inside. As hunters become gatherers and gatherers turn to agriculture, humankind learns to propagate their own hives close to home.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18502_ShortDesc", "A woven trap for fishing")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18502_LongDesc", "Much of humanity\'s earliest exercises in cunning and ingenuity came from staring at the water and devising an easier way to catch fish. Traps and nets are woven from various, tough fibers, and aid in man\'s pursuit of tasty fish.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18503_ShortDesc", "A submersible cage used to catch shellfish")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18503_LongDesc", "Much of humanity\'s earliest exercises in cunning and ingenuity came from staring at the water and devising an easier way to catch fish. Submersible cages made from wooden boards, and sometimes a mesh of metal, are employed in the pursuit of tasty shellfish.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18504_ShortDesc", "A wooden cask used in fermentation")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18504_LongDesc", "<span style=\"italic\">The dead are dead, and what has passed is done! I have a ship and a fighting crew and a girl with lips like wine, and that\'s all I ever asked. Lick your wounds, bullies, and break out a cask of ale.</> - The Pool of the Black One\n\nWhat better way to prove to a savage that civilization is good than to wet their fierce tongues with liquor, wine, or ale? The arts of fermentation give humankind the gift of drink and libation. These wooden barrels are the heart of that blessed task.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18505_ShortDesc", "A manual pressing machine")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18505_LongDesc", "This useful device presses and separates liquid from materials - such as oil from raw fish or seeds.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18506_ShortDesc", "Special rack for drying")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18506_LongDesc", "With some ingenuity, a specialized rack, oven or kiln might be used to dry certain materials. Drying meat can help to preserve it. Dried wood makes for a much better fire.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18507_ShortDesc", "A cold box for preserving")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18507_LongDesc", "Though salting and drying are common methods to preserve food, some use containers filled with ice to slow the process of decay.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18508_ShortDesc", "A cold box for preserving")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18508_LongDesc", "Though salting and drying are common methods to preserve food, some use containers filled with ice to slow the process of decay. This larger icebox holds more food and preserves it longer.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18509_ShortDesc", "A stone cooking surface")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18509_LongDesc", "Cooking brought indoors. Whereas cooking on a campfire merely involved throwing food on a pan and letting it burn, now the art of food preparation can become more complex and varied.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18510_ShortDesc", "Heavy, stone tool.")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18510_LongDesc", "With its circular action, this heavy, stone tool grinds greater masses of substances, more efficiently, than a simple mortar and pestle. It can be used to grind things like salt and spices down to useful granules and powders.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18512_ShortDesc", "A table with all the tools required for miscellaneous creations")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18512_LongDesc", "Sometimes a saw and a hammer are simply not enough. This worktable contains a variety of small tools that are uniquely suited to various tasks that involve the creation of dozens of miscellaneous objects.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18513_ShortDesc", "A worktable for the creation of saddles")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18513_LongDesc", "Straddling the line between art and craft, saddlery is the design and creation of saddles. Many civilized cities will boast several saddlers, competing for the attention of noblemen and the local military. In such places, only access to raw materials and imagination put limits on what can be created.\n\nOut here in the Exiled Lands, both raw materials and imagination are much harder to come by.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18514_ShortDesc", "A place for crafting objects of torture")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18514_LongDesc", "What elevates men above animals? Some scholars speculate that it is man's capacity for good that elevates him above the basic beast. 

Others, however, would argue that it is his infinite capacity for darkness.

This table, designed expressly for the purpose of crafting implements for inflicting pain and servitude on other peoples, is a good argument for the latter.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18515_ShortDesc", "A stone cooking surface")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18515_LongDesc", "Cooking brought indoors. Whereas cooking on a campfire merely involved throwing food on a pan and letting it burn, now the art of food preparation can become more complex and varied.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18519_ShortDesc", "A smelly pile of rotting matter")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18519_LongDesc", "Ask not a man what goes into his compost heap. That is his business alone. It is what a man removes from his compost heap that matters.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18520_ShortDesc", "A crude planter for slowly growing plants")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18520_LongDesc", "When man discovered the secrets of agriculture, the world changed. No longer roving bands of battling tribes, the first villages and cities formed around the idea that going out hunting food was a lot harder than just growing it safely behind walls.\n\nThis planter is very crude, and seeds sown in it will grow slowly.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18521_ShortDesc", "A planter for growing plants")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18521_LongDesc", "When man discovered the secrets of agriculture, the world changed. No longer roving bands of battling tribes, the first villages and cities formed around the idea that going out hunting food was a lot harder than just growing it safely behind walls.\n\nThis planter is a standard design, and seeds sown in it will grow at a regular rate.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18522_ShortDesc", "An improved planter for quickly growing plants")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18522_LongDesc", "When man discovered the secrets of agriculture, the world changed. No longer roving bands of battling tribes, the first villages and cities formed around the idea that going out hunting food was a lot harder than just growing it safely behind walls.\n\nSowing seeds in this planter will cause them to grow quickly over time.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18523_ShortDesc", "A bench covered in tools for crafting armor")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18523_LongDesc", "<span style=\"italic\">With the firelight glinting from his blue steel armor, he seemed like an image of steel - dynamic power for the moment quiescent; not resting, but motionless for the instant, awaiting the signal to plunge again into terrific action.</> - Black Colossus\n\nCreating armor, particularly metal armor, requires a large number of exotic tools. This armormaking bench can be used to create anything from the lightest leather armor to hardened steel armor. Provided that the raw materials are available, of course.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18525_ShortDesc", "A large chest for storing items")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18525_LongDesc", "Somewhere to place excess items and materials, this chest is made from sturdy materials. It can be locked against strangers, and all but the most determined thief will be deterred. No system is perfect, however.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18526_ShortDesc", "A bench for experimentation with materials and items")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18526_LongDesc", "Sometimes the greatest results occur when disciplines collide. Alchemy and herbalism, for example. Masonry and smithing to take another.\n\nThe delving bench is for those who wish to explore the deeper properties and interactions of items and materials. Experimentation can lead to great results - but there is always risk involved as well.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18997_ShortDesc", "A pen for holding horses")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18997_LongDesc", "If the humans are the masters of the age, then their mastery was built upon the backs of their animal servants. The humble oxen is slaughtered to feed the masses of Aquilonia, the humble plough horse clears the fields for grain to bake their bread, and sheep provide the wool which is spun to create their finery.

Animals can be loyal companions, or exploited for the resources that they produce.

The food that an animal is given as it grows is a major factor in determining the type of creature it will be once grown.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18999_ShortDesc", "A workbench equipped for dismantling armors and weapons")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_18999_LongDesc", "This workbench allows the disassembly of armors, weapons and building pieces into component parts - at some loss.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19000_ShortDesc", "A flower taken from the sacred grove of Jhebbal Sag")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19000_LongDesc", "<span style="italic">I've heard that there's an ancient grove sacred to Jhebbal Sag somewhere in this forest, said Conan. I don't know. I've never seen it. But more beasts remember in this country than any I've ever seen.</> - Beyond the Black River

The groves of Jhebbal Sag are said to be the places where the god walks when he chooses to visit this world. In the shamanic traditions of the Black Kingdom, the groves of Jhebbal Sag are spiritual places, reached only through meditation and the ingestion of certain mushrooms.

In the Pictish Wilderness, however, it is claimed that such a grove exists in the physical world.

Perhaps they are both one and the same place, and it is the astral voyaging of shamans that brings them face to face with the awesome power of Jhebbal Sag.

This flower, gathered in a place that may or may not have been a dream, can facilitate the power of Jhebbal Sag in beasts - increasing the chance of them growing larger and stronger.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19001_ShortDesc", "A rough pen for holding animals")
column4:

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19004_ShortDesc", "A hunk o\' crap")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19004_LongDesc", "Crap, muck, excrement, manure, feces, ordure, droppings - whatever it is called, it stinks. It probably makes good fertilizer.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19005_ShortDesc", "A box for feeding animals")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19005_LongDesc", "Forgetting to feed a group of dangerous creatures is usually not a problem for a very long time. Those who do, return to find a much smaller group of satiated and passive creatures.\nTo prevent this from happening, a stockpile of feed can be left behind in a box. That way the creatures that are still alive after the inevitable bloodbath will last a while longer.\nEfficient.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19006_ShortDesc", "A pot for feeding thralls")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19006_LongDesc", "Thralls in your... employ... will periodically take food out of this pot in order to not starve.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19050_ShortDesc", "A meal flavored with shadespice")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19050_LongDesc", "This meal has been seasoned with shadespice, created from the shadebloom which blossoms at midnight in the sacred groves of Jhebbal Sag. \nThe animal that eats this has a greatly increased chance of growing stronger and larger.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19161_ShortDesc", "The carcass of a camel")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19161_LongDesc", "Notorious for their glass jaw and tendency to spit, this camel was apparently killed by some form of head trauma. Life is harsh in the Exiled Lands, but more so for camels than any other creature as every idiot barbarian who passes by tries to punch them in the face.\n\nRest in peace, fair camel. You\'re safe now.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19500_ShortDesc", "Flesh which bears remembrance of Jhebbal Sag")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19500_LongDesc", "<span style="italic">Once all living things worshipped him. That was long ago, when beasts and men spoke one language. Men have forgotten him; even the beasts forget. Only a few remember. The men who remember Jhebbal Sag and the beasts who remember are brothers and speak the same tongue.</> - Beyond the Black River

There are very few now who remember Jhebbal Sag and his religions. Primarily in Pictland and the Black Kingdoms is he venerated.

But all men were once worshippers and they shared a language with the beasts of the world. In the midnight grove, a realm that exists purely in the thoughts of the god, a worthy challenger might confront their bestial nature and rather than overcome it, instead learn to be at peace with it.

This flesh awakens the ancient language within a person, restoring the worship of Jhebbal Sag to their hearts.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19501_ShortDesc", "A potion that allows communication with Jhebbal Sag")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19501_LongDesc", "<span style=\"italic\">Soon your ghost will talk with the ghosts of the Dark Land, and they will tell you of the old gods which are not dead, but sleep in the outer abysses, and from time to time awake.</> - Beyond the Black River\n\nBrewed from a combination of sacred herbs and mushrooms, this potion is supposed to facilitate communication directly with Jhebbal Sag. What that means exactly and how it works can only be discovered through experimentation.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19502_ShortDesc", "A potion that gives the ability to see in the dark")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19502_LongDesc", "<span style="italic">She strained her eyes into the blackness beyond the rim of the dim light, tense with fear of what she might see. A whimpering gasp escaped her lips. The darkness was taking form. Something huge and bulky grew up out of the void.</> - Xuthal of the Dusk

Some creatures have perfect vision even in the darkest of environments. Through the power of Jhebbal Sag, this potion confers the benefits of such night vision to the imbiber.

This gives an obvious advantage to those who would creep up on enemies during the darkest of nights, but also allows for freeing up hand during dungeon exploration.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19503_ShortDesc", "A potion that resets attribute points")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19503_LongDesc", "<span style="italic"> Men have forgotten him; even the beasts forget. Only a few remember. The men who remember Jhebbal Sag and the beasts who remember are brothers and speak the same tongue.</> - Beyond the Black River

This potion recalls the beast locked inside every person - pushing their ingrained instincts backwards and allowing them to retrain their body in new ways and forms.

Pictish warriors are often given this potion when they reach adulthood - and encouraged to realign their physical attributes with the totem beat of their tribe.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19504_ShortDesc", "A potion that resets feat points")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19504_LongDesc", "<span style=\"italic\">Civilized men laugh,\" said Conan. \"But not one can tell me how Zogar Sag can call pythons and tigers and leopards out of the wilderness and make them do his bidding. They would say it is a lie, if they dared. That\'s the way with civilized men. When they can\'t explain something by their half-baked science, they refuse to believe it.</> - Beyond the Black River\n\nThis potion clears the knowledge of civilization, wiping away learned skills until the imbiber is left with nothing more than a vast potential for learning. They are then free to sculpt their mind in whichever direction they wish.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19600_ShortDesc", "Shining, fish-like scales")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19600_LongDesc", "These scales were taken from one of the inhabitants of the sunken city. It can be used as an ingredient in a number of different potions and tinctures.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19605_ShortDesc", "Infused extract of the aloe plant")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19605_LongDesc", "Stygian traditions of healing hold that the aloe plant contains many desirable properties. In Luxur, the aloe is harvested for use in the temples of Derketo to cleanse blemishes from the skin of the priestesses. It is often used to sooth oozing wounds and those who ingest it claim that they feel a burst of wellbeing. Whether these effects are of the body or the mind is irrelevant - ingesting aloe extract seems to give the imbiber a regenerative health effect.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19606_ShortDesc", "Bandages used for binding wounds")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19606_LongDesc", "<span style=\"italic\">\'She sat on a couch with her wounded leg extended upon it, and the Tecuhltli woman had just bound it with silk bandages. Valeria\'s red-stained sword lay on the couch beside her.\'</> - Red Nails\n\nWounds require special care, to heal and to avoid infection and putrefaction. Sometimes, upon the battlefield, all one can do is bind a wound with strips of fiber.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19610_ShortDesc", "A submersible cage used to catch shellfish")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19610_LongDesc", "Much of humanity\'s earliest exercises in cunning and ingenuity came from staring at the water and devising an easier way to catch fish. Submersible cages made from wooden boards, and sometimes a mesh of metal, are employed in the pursuit of tasty shellfish.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19611_ShortDesc", "A woven trap for fishing")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_19611_LongDesc", "Much of humanity\'s earliest exercises in cunning and ingenuity came from staring at the water and devising an easier way to catch fish. Traps and nets are woven from various, tough fibers, and aid in man\'s pursuit of tasty fish.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_24116_ShortDesc", "A sealed leather skin for storing water")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_24116_LongDesc", "<span style="italic"> Let him wait until we get to camp. It's only ten miles. If he's fit to live in the desert he'll live that long without a drink.</> - A Witch Shall be Born

Pitch has been used to seal this waterskin, slowing the inevitable leaks and keeping the water level stable. The addition of pitch, however, adds a nasty sulphurous aftertaste to the water.

To combat this aftertaste, aloe leaves have been sown into the lining of the waterskin, reducing the nasty aftertaste and adding a minor healing property to the water.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30000_ShortDesc", "A note scrawled on flimsy paper")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30000_LongDesc", "I have seen many things in these lands, Exile. Know that these tomes contain some of my more esoteric finds - some awe-inspiring and yet others... awful. Access to this library can only be obtained by the offering of one of many fragments spread across this city. Find them, bring them here and the knowledge shall be yours.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30001_ShortDesc", "A note scrawled on flimsy paper")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30001_LongDesc", "I am beaten. Left to rot among the ruins of the past.
There are others here. Slaves, bandits and cannibals. Exiles from lands I've never heard of.
Some of them try to scrape a life from the wasteland, scrabbling in the rocks and sand for their own place.
I cannot go on. The life that I left behind haunts me. The sun over the glittering spires of Belverus is forever denied me. The smell of my daughter's hair...
I will pass the ghost fence and this cursed land will finally end me. 
To whoever reads this note, I leave the last of my water and this message.
Stranger, you have my pity. You do not know how cursed you truly are.
")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30002_ShortDesc", "A leather journal")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30002_LongDesc", "Gods curse this sandstorm! 
We were forced to take refuge before the wind scoured the skin from our faces. 
There is something in the storm. Beasts. We hear the skittering of their paws outside the ruins and their howls mingled with the screaming winds.
The men are scared. I've put them to work crafting rudimentary weapons and torches from the loose stones and rough plants that dot this place.
I've yet to meet a beast that liked fire, or the bite of the axe.
")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30003_ShortDesc", "A brief prayer to Hanuman")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30003_LongDesc", "Oh lord of the darkness,
Of men who are not men,
Give us strength and suffering,
In equal measure.

Let our bodies be pleasing to you,
And our minds quieted from this conscious thought.
Let us find the inner rages,
And loose them upon the earth.

We give our sacrifice into your hands,
Appease your thirst in the slickness of blood.
Grant us the power of your might,
The eternal strength of Hanuman.
")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30004_ShortDesc", "A note speculating about the nature of strength")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30004_LongDesc", "What is strength? I find myself pondering that question more and more as the days turn.
I've seen strong, confident men killed because they tried to fight when they should have run away. I've 
seen those who people consider weak, sharing their food with others and gaining their gratitude and 
protection.
In the past, I was a blacksmith and I was considered the strongest man in my village. But I sold a sword 
to the wrong man, and ended up here.
And now that I am here, I see clearly that it is the things that I know - how to work the forge and the 
creation of weapons and tools - that carries true value.
Knowledge is strength. That is the lesson.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30005_ShortDesc", "A piece of parchment with crazed scribblings")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30005_LongDesc", "Nowhere is safe. Nowhere. The drums come every night now, a rhythmic pounding that raises terror in 
every heartbeat.
The Darfari are hunting and men are their quarry.
I used to hear their drums out in the desert groves beyond Zamboula and in that life, I simply thanked 
the gods that I had wealth and shelter.
But see me now, crouched among the boulders, filthy, ragged and half starved. My days are a constant 
scramble for food and water and my nights are spent huddled in whatever shelter I can find.
Soon I will drift off to the half-sleep of the terrified, to dream of filed teeth and wicked cudgels and the 
haunting beating of those gods-cursed drums...
")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30006_ShortDesc", "A journal entry written by Razma the Exile")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30006_LongDesc", "When my father died, I knew they would be coming for me. It was only a matter of time.
What I didn't expect was this....to be crucified and left to rot on the edge of a wasteland that I have 
never seen before.

It makes sense to me that the cowardly fools that they sent to do the job would not have the courage to 
kill me. They are mongrels, the cast off bloodlines of slaves and commoners, and such as they do not 
dare to spill royal blood.

Instead, I was bound hand, foot and mouth and smuggled out to god knows where.

They left me for the vultures, but I was rescued by a man. 

Such a man! Clean-limbed and bronze-skinned, I have never seen his like in the citystates that dot the 
meadowlands of Shem. He came to me as I hung from the cross and his icy blue stare was a challenge. 

Did I dare to live?

Now I crouch at the edge of this wasteland, once a daughter of princes, now a nameless exile in an 
unfamiliar land. In my hands, the shaft of the double-bladed axe that he gave me is a comforting weight. 

The answer is yes. I will live.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30007_ShortDesc", "A journal entry written by Razma the Exile")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30007_LongDesc", "I am not alone here. That was the first revelation that came to me as I crouched, shivering, on the banks of the river. There are others, ragged and broken men and women, who light bonfires on the shores of the river and huddle close together for warmth.

Fools. The light draws unfriendly eyes and I would never put myself at such risk.

My father always taught me that the best way to survive was not to make the mistakes that other people make. Life is not always about the choices we make, but about the foolish choices we avoid making. 

But father is dead and I am alone in the darkness.
")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30008_ShortDesc", "A journal entry written by Razma the Exile")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30008_LongDesc", "My father told me that there is something to be learned from all the peoples of the world. I do not yet know what these Darfari will teach me.

I was captured as I moved north from the river. They clubbed me senseless and dragged me back to their camp, thrusting me into a woven cage full of prisoners.

They've been dragging us out, one by one, to their sacrifice pits. The screams of the victims fill the air and the scent... my mouth waters and I hate myself.

I've seen the bloody sacrifices that Set requires and the corpulent orgies of Derketo, but these brutes with filed teeth and blood running down their chins... I don't like this darkness. It makes my skin crawl.

Some of the other prisoners here are from further north. One of them claims to be a Stygian bounty hunter who came here chasing treasure. He says there is a whole city of them in the north.

And in the cage beside us is a woman who is dressed...like a pirate? Does that mean we are somewhere near the ocean?

I need answers. I've been so busy running. Surviving. 

There's a loose branch on the weaving of this cage. My Stygian friend and I are working it slowly loose and then we will vanish into the night.

I realize now that I have been foolish to avoid others. If I am to escape these exiled lands, I need to find people who know what the stakes are. I need other people. 

Lesson learned.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30009_ShortDesc", "A journal entry written by Razma the Exile")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30009_LongDesc", "I walk among giants.

My Stygian friend (his name is Jakkad) and I found this place after we fled the Darfari. I can't even say for certain that we managed to lose them - they shied away from entering this place. Perhaps they consider it sacred.

When we came to the entrance, our bracelets flared and the tablets by the great door were lit from within by a light like devil's fire.

A voice spoke within our minds, alien, arrogant. It spoke and in my mind I saw the black spires of an ancient city and the stately, unearthly creatures that dwelt within.

I fell down in a faint, dreaming as one who has inhaled the pollen of the Black Lotus.

In my dream, I walked with them along black stone avenues and sat with them as they communed with primordial beings and took counsel with blasphemous minds from outside the veil. I watched as they observed humans entering their lands, at first amused and then alarmed.

I watched as they changed, hardening their hearts against the humans who came to them, begging for refuge. They sealed their borders. They enslaved the humans that they captured. They bonded them, with these bracelets that we wear today.

When I awoke, hours later, Jakkad and I spoke of what I had seen. Apparently, he had none of my visions, just heard the voice in his mind warning him to stay away from this place.

It is becoming clear to me that there is more going on here than just the politics that I learned at the feet of my foster-father. There are answers to be found. For those who would seek. ")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30010_ShortDesc", "A journal entry written by Razma the Exile")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30010_LongDesc", "I think I must be dreaming. I visited pirates today. Pirates! In the middle of a desert!

It's as ridiculous as it sounds. Landlocked pirates who've built themselves a ship of stone and iron on a mesa in the middle of a canyon. They dress in pirate garb and call themselves 'The Black Hand'.

They claim to be searching for a way out of the Exiled Lands, the same as Jakked and I, but it doesn't seem as though they have made much progress. There was a lot of talk about hidden maps and secret treasures. I did not speak to their leader, the Butcher of Khwarizm, but I saw her from a distance. A formidable woman. Whatever these fools who follow her think, she has a real plan.

Jakkad and I have agreed to continue west. According to Jakkad there are more ruins out there - an entire city! - though he claims that it is dangerous. But beyond it, in the northwest is the city where his people can be found.

Our search continues...")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30011_ShortDesc", "A journal entry written by Razma the Exile")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30011_LongDesc", "Jakkad is gone. Swallowed by the darkness and desolation. A winged demon screeches a haunting dirge as it flees with my companion towards the stars.
 
Ever since we took our first steps into this city, we knew that something was waiting for us. The darkness is a tide, lapping at the shore of my sanity, eroding it. Blood seeps from wounds I didn't know I had. 

The ruins cast insane shadows on the landscape and they cast a shadow on my mind. The past and the present run together in my mind and..
I am a slave rushing to help my master and..
I am a woman screaming in the ruins and..
I am a god planning wars and wickedness and..
I am a sandstorm, scouring the lands and..

I am... myself. Alone. Exiled.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30012_ShortDesc", "A journal entry written by Razma the Exile")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30012_LongDesc", "For a long time, I drifted between worlds. I dreamed of lives that I never lived, faces that I never knew, loves that I never had. And in one of my dreams, I found the answer. But I must return to the city. And I dare not do that alone. 

I don't know where they found me, these rough people dressed in the skins of hyenas. They carried me back to their camp - somewhere north of the city, and left me sleeping on a pile of furs by one of their tents.
I don't think they expected me to wake up.

I've been watching them while pretending to sleep. There is something very strange going on. Their body language is wrong. I grew up on the streets of Asgalun and I could read the body of a haggling merchant before I could walk. 

But these people... They remind me of the mangy curs that used to wander the streets, begging for scraps. They stand too close. They sniff at one another. When one of them shouts, the others cower.

I need to get out of here. 

They are gathering in the old arena among the ruins, howling like hyenas. They are performing some ritual. A naked man is cloaked in a blood soaked Hyena skin.

I dare not waste this chance. I must slip away.

I will go west and find Jakkad's people. I'm going to need their help.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30013_ShortDesc", "A journal entry written by Razma the Exile")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30013_LongDesc", "I am ready.

Jakkad's people were skeptical when I first stumbled into their city. But they knew his name and then... Shemites! My countrymen! Familiar faces. Some recognized my face, but I quieted them with a glance.

It has been good for me to be here. I have been able to rest and relax. The Exiled Lands are a fearsome place, but the people here have managed to build something.

I have spoken with men who have been here for a score of years. They told me of the Purge, when soldiers ride through the land, slaying and pillaging. They have told me of the sandstorms that arise with such fury out of nowhere and disappear just as quickly.

I told them of the vision I had in the ruined city. Of the room, nestling beneath the secret heart of the ruins. Of the map, which shows the land that traps us. Of the gems, which can free us all.

They've agreed to send an expedition. I will lead them into the ruins.

And then... to freedom.

I leave the last page of my journal here. My journey thus far has been one written. Action speaks louder than words.

May we never meet again in the Exiled Lands. 

- Razma of Shem")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30014_ShortDesc", "A note etched into a block of wood")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30014_LongDesc", "By the gods, they're going to eat me! The drums are beating in frenzied rhythm and the Darfari savages are dancing around a pit of swirling flames.
I've seen what happens to those who are cast into the pit - the screams as the searing heat consumes them.
If you are, like me, a captive of these devils then I can offer no comfort. But if you are a free man and can read these words then I would ask a boon of you: Salaceo of the Black Hand pretended to be my friend and then traded me to these savages for animal hides.
He needed my skills as a scribe to write down directions to the place where he keeps his treasures, lest he forget the path. But then because of my knowledge of his hiding place, he sold me to the Darfari.
But I prepared for this eventuality. I wrote his instructions down incorrectly. If you find him, kill him. Do not offer quarter or mercy. Take his instructions, by way of thanks.
But remember that for every step I wrote, I took two.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30015_ShortDesc", "A brief report about desertions from the Black Hand")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30015_LongDesc", "As ordered, we tracked the deserters into the southern desert. We found Old Colby here hidden in the shelter of a rocky outcrop, muttering to himself. Of the others, there was no sign.
I asked Colby to tell me what happened, and I got this wild tale which I have written down in full.

"We weren't desertin', we was off huntin' for treasure! Jacoby had it in 'is mind that them broodin' 
ruins, the ones that the bracelet calls The Observatory was full of treasures. 
Jacoby got me and the boys to follow along, an' he took us to the cliff with a length o' stout rope an' a 
plan to go climbin'.
Well, the ascent was steep an' dangerous, on account of us doin' it during the nighttime to avoid them 
cannibals as haunts the area, but we picked a nice clear night with a full moon and got ourselves to the 
very top.
I gotta say, I didna like them ruins from the moment we got there. Just a pile o black brooding stone in 
the moonlight and no treasure in sight.
Jacoby starts poking around, lookin for the treasure an all and he uncovers one of them glowing tablets. 
That voice - you know the one - starts talkin' about constellations and star signs and the crew starts 
swearin' and cursin Jacoby for dragging us up for nothin and then it came...
I ain't ever seen anything like it, mate. It had skin like a plague corpse and black bristlin' fur. It's red eyes 
were glowin' like the coals of hell and when it reared up, the wings blotted out the moonlight.
It took Jacoby first, just snappin forward and tearing 'is head clean off.
Me and the boys were screamin' and scramblin', trying to reach the rope and get down afore this beasty 
could take us.
I got to the rope and started slidin' down, burnin' my hands as I went. Above, I could hear the screamin' 
and snapping and warm blood was a rainin' from the sky. The rope was swayin' and slappin' me into the 
cliffface and I was scramblin' and then... it let go.
I fell and I fell, but I crashed into the top of a tree and I passed out.
When I awoke, I was alone out here in the desert, with a sandstorm sweepin' in. I got meself to some 
shelter and then you found me here."

I'm bringing Colby back to the ship for judgement. Personally, I think we can hang him from the edge. 
He's obviously lying to protect the others.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30016_ShortDesc", "A drinking song of questionable quality")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30016_LongDesc", "Sing, sing to the broken road,
Paved in the oaths of forgotten men,
And blood and bones that churned the sand,
The bitter heart of a traitors den.

Behold the swollen corpses song,
Croaked from the throats of hanging fools,
Pattering feet in a rictus jig,
Come to the rope our eager ghouls!

Listen now to the wind swung souls,
Diving down to the rocks and sand,
Holding their tongues in bloat and decay,
Never again to cross The Black Hand.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30017_ShortDesc", "Salaceo\'s Instructions")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30017_LongDesc", "On the EAST side of the Black hand Ship, there is an anchor.
From the Anchor, take 45 steps (walk don't run) NORTH
Turn EAST, take 50 steps, then turn SOUTH and take 25 more steps.
Finally, turn EAST and take 150 steps. 
There, hidden at the base of a mighty tree, is my chest.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30019_ShortDesc", "A leather bound journal")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30019_LongDesc", "It is amazing to me that the other people who share this place with me call this The Exiled Lands. If I could name it, I would call it the Blessed Lands, because it truly is a place of great blessings.

In my youth, I was a rash and foolish man, the youngest son of a minor noble of Poitain. At that age I was consumed by my love of wealth and status and I drank and gambled with other young men of questionable character.

Eventually my father, when confronted with my gambling debts, gave me no choice. He simply shipped me off to a monastery, to contemplate my sins.

I was not an admirable monk, I confess freely. More concerned with my own amusement than the state of my soul, I often stole from the monastery by night and returned with stolen casks of ale and food. I was popular among the other monks, of course, but the Abbot began to see my influence upon his entire congregation.

Eventually, he decided to be rid of me.
One night I awoke, bound hand and foot with sturdy ropes, while two burly men lifted me from my bunk and carried me down the winding stone staircase of the monastery. The Abbot accompanied them, wringing his hands and pleading to me with his eyes.

"My child, the choice breaks my heart, but I am losing the others. These men will take you away, somewhere far away, where you can start a new life away from your father or Mitra. It will be the best for this monastery and the best for you. Tell me that you understand?" he pleaded.

"What if they decided to slit my throat, Abbot? Then my death will be on your hands." I spat.

"I have assurances that they will not." He glanced nervously at the men carrying me. "I wish you the best of your new life, child". He turned away.

I was put into the back of a wagon, covered with a sackcloth, and left to my terrified thoughts.

For how long I traveled, I cannot say. I was passed from one set of hands to another, always with the clink of gold to seal the exchange. Other captives joined me in the wagon - men and women from different lands. Some were nobleman, some were commoners. All were as confused as I was about where we were going and why. Most of us assumed that our captors were Shemitish slavers.

On the last night of my old life, we were given our rations, a thick heavy stew of vegetables and meat. Like the others, I ate ravenously. And like the others, when whatever poison they had put into the food kicked in, the darkness swallowed me.

The next day, my new life began.
I awoke, stripped naked, in the sands of a vast desert. There were no people to be seen, just some ruins and the vast emptiness of the sands. I was disoriented, but I chose a direction and set out, hoping to find anybody or anything.

I almost died. A sandstorm came sweeping in, swirling sand and lightning and I fled before it, taking shelter in the shadow on an old tumbled statue.
There were beasts in the sandstorm. I could hear them moving around and howling with the screeching wind.

I repented my life then, thinking of my family for the first time in years. I prayed to Mitra to protect my soul and I forgave the Abbot, who had been a good man trying to protect his flock.

Mitra spoke to me then, and his words were for me alone. He wrapped me in his presence, and kept the creatures from finding me. I gave myself wholly to Mitra, there in the darkest hour of my life. 

I came from the desert a new man and, guided by Mitra, I found this place. This shrine is dedicated to my god and to every Exiled soul, far from home and weary, who could use a place to rest.

I leave this story here in the hope that it will inspire others. I have gone ahead, deeper into the Exiled Lands. Mitra has told me that there is much work to do.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30023_ShortDesc", "A page from a mercenary\'s diary")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30023_LongDesc", "Low risk, high pay they said. Bah, I should have listened to my instincts. But how could I have foreseen 
this? Every now and then a deal goes sour and if your wit and sword are sharp, you can usually land on 
your feet, but this? 
The notice was under the seal of King Ctesphon himself, calling for adventurers and mercenaries 
interested in making good gold for little work to meet at the central plaza in Khemi. I was out of work 
and out of coin and there was nothing odd about the notice. Every so often the bandits who haunt the 
desert highways grow too bold and the King hires a small army of ruffians to scare them back into their 
hideouts for a while. It's boring work out in the desert with nary a whore or tavern in sight, but it pays 
well and bandits are more interested in running away from overwhelming odds than fighting so your 
chances of coming back again are pretty good. Better than any war I've ever fought in.
In any case, I thought this would be the same thing. But it wasn't.
Quite a few of us gathered at the muster in the square - mostly Stygian, of course, but there were a few 
freebooters from the northern lands. They stood in their own little group, some distance from the rest 
of us, looking uneasy.
The royal guards showed up and cleared a space in the center of the square for the royal herald.
"We're looking for treasure hunters" he announced, looking around the square at the assorted scum 
that the summons had gathered. "We've discovered the ruins of an ancient city and we need those souls 
brave enough to travel into the ruins and recover all of treasures found therein. For every treasure that 
you recover, you will be paid a sum of gold. The ruins are, as far as we can tell, uninhabited. Because we 
don't want the whereabouts of these ruins - and the treasure- to become common knowledge, if you 
agree to join us there are three conditions.
Firstly, you will be blindfolded and transported by wagon to the ruins.
Secondly, you will not be allowed to have contact with anybody outside of the ruins while you are 
there.
And finally, you will wear one of these." He was holding up a golden bracelet, which glinted with a green jewel. I was too far away to make out much detail but I remember thinking immediately that the price of 
the bracelet - if it was real - was worth taking the job for anyway.
"What's the trick?" A burly, leather-clad man holding a fearsome looking maul demanded. I agreed. 
Something was not right here. This all sounded far too good to be true.
"The trick" said a black robed man, pushing past the royal herald to confront the mercenary who had 
shouted, "is really very simple." He lifted an arm, and it was clear that he was holding a golden bracelet 
exactly like the one that the herald had been holding a moment before.
"If you try to keep anything you find in the ruins, or you run away from the ruins with the thought that 
you might sell this bracelet - you will be punished" The man in the black robe flicked his hand and it 
wasn't a golden bracelet he was holding, but a small golden snake with glittering green eyes. He threw it 
full in to the face of the burly mercenary.
The man shrieked and clawed at his face, but it was far too late. He began to convulse, frothing at the 
mouth and turning a dreaful pale color. He fell to the ground, still twitching.
The man in the black robe stepped over the dying man, and picked up the glittering snake from the 
ground. By the time he did, it was simply a bracelet once more.
The crowd murmured uneasily. We were used to the priests of Set and their bloody knives, but such 
blatant sorcery implied a pact with even darker powers, the type of pact that stains a mans soul in 
darkness that can never be erased.
"Now, if our terms are acceptable to you, please step forward." The royal herald has stepped forward to 
talk to the crowd again, the black robed sorcerer had withdrawn back behind the guards.
About half of the crowd moved toward the herald immediately, eager for the adventure. Quite a few 
people left immediately, clearly disquieted by the demonstration of power that they had seen.
I lingered. I'm not a superstitious man, but I knew there were things beyond my understanding in this 
world and I wanted no part of them. 
On the other hand, my purse was hanging limply at my side and my lips were parched for lack of strong 
drink.
I should have listened to my instincts. But I chose the path of the fool, and now I am destined to die in 
the Exiled Lands. Just another exile, lost in the desert...")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30024_ShortDesc", "A waterstained parchment")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30024_LongDesc", "This note has been under the water for a long time and most of the words have been washed away.
What is left reads:
...enius plan! If it is buried in...
...st pillar, opposite the riv...
...neath the skull of a mammoth...
...ash it! The only...")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30049_ShortDesc", "Flesh which bears remembrance of Jhebbal Sag")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30049_LongDesc", "<span style="italic">Once all living things worshipped him. That was long ago, when beasts and men spoke one language. Men have forgotten him; even the beasts forget. Only a few remember. The men who remember Jhebbal Sag and the beasts who remember are brothers and speak the same tongue.</> - Beyond the Black River

There are very few now who remember Jhebbal Sag and his religions. Primarily in Pictland and the Black Kingdoms is he venerated.

But all men were once worshippers and they shared a language with the beasts of the world. In the midnight grove, a realm that exists purely in the thoughts of the god, a worthy challenger might confront their bestial nature and rather than overcome it, instead learn to be at peace with it.

This flesh awakens the ancient language within a person, restoring the worship of Jhebbal Sag to their hearts.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30050_ShortDesc", "A scroll that teaches the precepts of Mitra")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30050_LongDesc", "The precepts of Mitra are simple when compared to the myriad of other cults and religions that dominate the Hyborian Age.

This simple document contains all that one needs to become a worshipper of the gentle god. The fact that it must be read, however, is a testament to the subtlety of the Mitra cult. For it ensures that only those who are intelligent enough to read will naturally join the religion - and those who cannot will be guided by one who can.

This scroll will unlock the Mitra religion.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30051_ShortDesc", "A fragment of ice that echoes with strange knowledge")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30051_LongDesc", "This icicle radiates a cold so intense that it almost burns the flesh to touch it. Icicles such as this are said to be fragments of ice shaken from the beard of Ymir as he takes vengeance upon his enemies. They never melt, but lie where they are fallen until they are discovered by shamans, who undertake vision quests to discover them.

When a non-believer holds such an icicle, it melts into their skin and fills them with the knowledge of Ymir and his religion.

Using this icicle will teach the Ymir religion.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30052_ShortDesc", "A skull that chants the teachings of Yog")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30052_LongDesc", "This skull has eyes that burn with the eternal fire of Yog. When held to the ear, like a seashell, one can hear the eternal chanting of Yog.

Whether this skull was once the victim of Yog, or a true believer who sacrificed themselves to a higher purpose, it now serves as a vessel for the gibberings of the cannibal god.

Using this skull will teach the Yog religion.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30053_ShortDesc", "A glittering gem that mesmerizes those who stare too deeply")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30053_LongDesc", "<span style="italic">Under the caverned pyramids great Set coils asleep;</>
<span style="italic">Among the shadows of the tombs his dusky people creep.</>
<span style="italic">I speak the Word from the hidden gulfs that never knew the sun</>
<span style="italic">Send me a servant for my hate, oh scaled and shining One!</> - The Phoenix on the Sword

This gem, and others like it, were once used by Priests of Set in their most sacred rituals. It is gravest heresy to discuss such rites, but they involved serpents, sacrifices and blood.

This gem is said to be the eye of a real serpent, hardened to stone by the ritual, containing the wisdom and power of Set. One need only stare deeply into the stone to be mesmerized by the power of Set.

Using this gem will teach the Set religion.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30054_ShortDesc", "A clay tablet depicting the mysteries of Derketo")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30054_LongDesc", "Initiation into the temple of Derketo is difficult both physically and mentally. The extreme demands upon the body as well as the intense focus required strain the body and mind to the point of breaking.

This tablet depicts the seven sacred position of Derketo - erotic stylings shaped into hardened clay.

Focusing on the tablet sends a warmth through the body and a tingling in the senses. A surge of desire and an innate understanding of bodily energies. A whisper that tickles the ear and the wisdom of the goddess...

Using this tablet will teach the Derketo religion.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30098_ShortDesc", "A sealed leather skin for storing water")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_30098_LongDesc", "<span style="italic"> Let him wait until we get to camp. It's only ten miles. If he's fit to live in the desert he'll live that long without a drink.</> - A Witch Shall be Born

Pitch has been used to seal this waterskin, slowing the inevitable leaks and keeping the water level stable. The addition of pitch, however, adds a nasty sulphurous aftertaste to the water.

The Zuagirs and other tribes of the eastern deserts of Shem have long had the practise of soaking the outside of their waterskins before a long journey. As water evaporates from the outside of the skin, it cools the contents. Some enterprising merchants have been known to use the same trick to chill their wines when on a long journey.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_41020_ShortDesc", "A patch kit for repairing damaged armor")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_41020_LongDesc", "<span style="italic">Conan's dark scarred face was darker yet with passion; his black armor was hacked to tatters and splashed with blood; his great sword red to the cross-piece.</> - The Scarlet Citadel

A warrior needs to be able to rely on their armor in the heat of battle. When the broadswords swing, a layer of leather or steel can mean the difference between life and death.

This patch kit, containing scraps of metals, leather and hide, can be used to repair the most egregious insults to a piece of armor, though it will never be able to repair them completely.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_41024_ShortDesc", "A toolkit for repairing damaged weapons")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_41024_LongDesc", "<span style="italic">He rushed in, hacking madly, but Conan, recognizing him, shattered his sword with a short terrific chop and with a powerful push of his open hand sent him reeling to the floor.</> - The Phoenix on the Sword

When the fury of battle has subsided and the lightning clash of weapons has stilled, the victors are left to count the cost. And sometimes the price of battle is the very weapons that are used to wage it.

This kit, containing a whetstone, a hone and a small portion of blade oil, will allow even unskilled crafters to repair the worst damage to their blades, though it will never be able to renew them completely.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_41051_ShortDesc", "A fitting that can be applied to almost any weapon to reduce stamina cost")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_41051_LongDesc", "Most weapons, when crafted, are designed to a generic standard. Rarely do they account for the variation among individuals - height, strength, reach and balance.\n\nThis fitting, which can easily be altered to match almost any weapon, can change the center of balance to fit the idiosyncrasies of the wielder. This leads to more efficient, less strenuous swings that in turn leads to less strain on the stamina of the wielder.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_41052_ShortDesc", "A bag of unpleasant things that can be attached to weapons to increase their damage")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_41052_LongDesc", "Some warriors adorn their weapons to intimidate their foes and make them a memorable presence on the battlefield.

But the collection of spikes and studs contained in this bag have a single purpose - to wreck foes. Whether hammer, sword, or spear - there is something here to bring ruination, laceration, and devastation to the bodies and minds of enemies everywhere.

Applying this simple kit to a weapon will increase its damage slightly.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_41056_ShortDesc", "An assortment of upgrades to make tools more efficient")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_41056_LongDesc", "There is wisdom among the simple peoples of the world; those who spend their time tilling, hunting, growing and harvesting.

The time-tested techniques for improving the harvesting capacity of tools have been distilled into the upgrades found in this kit.

Applying this simple upgrade to a tool will increase its harvesting capacity slightly.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_41059_ShortDesc", "A blunted fitting that can be applied to a weapon to increase concussive damage")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_41059_LongDesc", "Sometimes the best course in combat is not to defeat an enemy, but to see them humiliated and begging for mercy. Or dragged back to spend some time whimpering on the Wheel of Pain.

This fitting can be attached to almost any weapon and increases the chance of knocking an enemy out before they bleed to death.

Applying this simple fitting will increase the concussion damage of a weapon slightly.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_41063_ShortDesc", "A kit that can be used to reduce the weight of a weapon")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_41063_LongDesc", "This paring blade is designed to shave slivers of metal from weapons and tools, thus allowing a decrease in weight while maintaining the strength and durability of the weapon.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_41064_ShortDesc", "A reinforcement that can be used to make weapons and armor more durable")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_41064_LongDesc", "A warrior relies on their strength, their skill and their weapon to carry them in battle. If any of these are broken in the clash of swords, it puts life and limb at risk.

This reinforcement can be used to find the flaws in a weapon or piece of armor and buttress them against the storm of battle.

This simple reinforcement will increase the durability of a weapon or piece of armor slightly.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_41067_ShortDesc", "A spiked fitting that can be applied to a weapon to increase armor penetration")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_41067_LongDesc", "When an opponent is covered in a layer of solid steel, it can be hard to find weak locations to strike. This modification solves that problem by providing the fastest way .\n\nApplying this fitting will increase the armor penetration of a weapon.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_41068_ShortDesc", "A kit used to identify and remove superfluous weight from armor")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_41068_LongDesc", "In the Exiled Lands, armor can range from the bone and feathers of the Darfari to the heavy plate worn by members the Silent Legion.
Due to cultural stylings, many of these armors include elements that are not necessary to the primary purpose of armor - protection.

This kit contains various tools for identifying and removing additional weight from a set of armor, while still maintaining its protective properties.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_41069_ShortDesc", "A set of reinforcing plates that can attached to increase the strength of armor")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_41069_LongDesc", "Designed to protect in battle, it can be disastrous if armor shatters beneath a powerful blow. Wise warriors seek to shore up their weaknesses, often by reinforcing the weaker joints of their armor.\n\nAttaching these thin plates to any set of clothing will increase its armor value slightly.")

Wise warriors seek to shore up their weaknesses, often by reinforcing the weaker joints of their armor.\n\nAttaching these plates to any set of clothing will increase its armor value.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_41071_ShortDesc", "A set of reinforcing plates that can attached to increase the strength of armor")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_41071_LongDesc", "Designed to protect in battle, it can be disastrous if armor shatters beneath a powerful blow. Wise warriors seek to shore up their weaknesses, often by reinforcing the weaker joints of their armor.\n\nAttaching these thick plates to any set of clothing will increase its armor value considerably.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_41072_ShortDesc", "A set of tools for improving the poise of a set of armor")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_41072_LongDesc", "In Poitain, the shining southern province of Aquilonia, it is common for men to engage in contests of arms wearing full plate armor. And among those people it is commonly understood that a once a warrior falls in full plate, they will be battling to return to their feet.

This kit, developed by the smiths of that fair land, is designed to resettle the weight of the armor set such that it matches the wearers center of balance. This means less chance of falling in battle and more time spent on the feet.

This simple kit will increase the poise value of armor slightly.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_41075_ShortDesc", "A set of tools for making armor more pliant and flexible")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_41075_LongDesc", "Uri the Mastersmith once stated that creating an armor set was a balance of three forces - flexibility, strength and coverage. He claimed that in developing a suit of armor, you could have two of these things, but never three. He demonstrated this principle by crafting the King of Nemedia a suit of armor that made him completely impervious to assassins; but also left the King completely unable to move once encased within.
Uri was executed not long afterward.

This small kit contains tools for stretching leather and working metal joints to make them more pliable. 

Using this simple kit on an armor set will make it slightly more flexible when climbing.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_50515_ShortDesc", "An ancient weapon found in the Unnamed City")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_50515_LongDesc", "Made from the bones and claws of the Winged Death, these arrows cause tremendous damage.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_50516_ShortDesc", "An ancient weapon found in the Unnamed City")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_50516_LongDesc", "An inscription reads \'Do not throw this away or it will be forever lost\'.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_50517_ShortDesc", "An ancient weapon found in the Unnamed City")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_50517_LongDesc", "xx_longdesc")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_50518_ShortDesc", "An ancient weapon found in the Unnamed City")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_50518_LongDesc", "<span style=\"italic\">It wheeled at the thud of her soft boots on the floor, but even as it turned, her keen blade lashed down, and a fierce exultation swept her as she felt the edge cleave solid flesh and mortal bone.</> - Red Nails\n\nHeld in the off-hand, these axes can be used for hacking at enemy shields and, in an emergency, hurled at their faces.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51084_ShortDesc", "One-handed short spear of ancient design")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51084_LongDesc", "<span style="italic">It's too ancient to be holy. Who ever saw metal like it in a sane world?</> - The God in the Bowl

The javelin is one of the most versatile weapons of the Hyborian age. Of course, this javelin is not of the Hyborian Age - it's ancient design is based upon writings from thousands of years ago.

In addition, the javelin is light enough to be thrown with some degree of accuracy. Enemies fleeing a battle are almost always surprised to find three feet of spear jutting from between their shoulder blades.

When equipped, this javelin seems to whisper to its bearer in the long forgotten language of the Giant-Kings. This constant distraction drains the willpower of the user, but those who master it may uncover hidden strengths.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51102_ShortDesc", "A blunted javelin for knocking out foes")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51102_LongDesc", "<span style="italic">I watched my opportunity and captured a Shemitish jailer - knocked him senseless as he left the courtyard late one night - dragged him into a cellar near by and questioned him.</> - A Witch Shall be Born

Sometimes an enemy will fight to the death. Sometimes an enemy will flee like a coward.

With this blunted javelin, a single well-placed throw can put down a fleeing enemy for interrogation and humiliation at a later point. 

It can be used in regular melee, of course, but it is somewhat less effective at stabbing than a regular pointed weapon.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51103_ShortDesc", "A blunted arrow for taking down enemies at range")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51103_LongDesc", "Originally designed for knocking birds from the air without damaging their meat and feathers, blunted arrows quickly became a staple of thieves and thugs who preferred to take their victims down from a distance.

The problem with using blunted arrows in combat is that they do very little damage, so the archer has to be accurate or risk the rage of a bruised, charging foe.

Arrows can be equipped by dragging them over the bow in the inventory.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51104_ShortDesc", "A blunted bolt for taking down enemies at range")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51104_LongDesc", "Originally designed for knocking birds from the air without damaging their meat and feathers, blunted bolts quickly became a staple of thieves and thugs who preferred to take their victims down from a distance.\n\nThe problem with using blunted bolts in combat is that they do very little damage, so the crossbowman has to be accurate or risk the rage of a bruised, charging foe.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51184_ShortDesc", "Primitive arrows made from bone")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51184_LongDesc", "<span style="italic">Better if steel and bowstring prevail without further aid from the arts, for the constant use of mighty spells sometimes sets forces in motion that might rock the universe.</> - The Hour of the Dragon

A well-made arrow can be the difference between a hit and a miss.

Arrows can be equipped by dragging them over the bow in the inventory.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51185_ShortDesc", "Primitive bolts made from bone")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51185_LongDesc", "<span style=\"italic\">Arus the watchman grasped his crossbow with shaky hands, and he felt beads of clammy perspiration on his skin as he stared at the unlovely corpse sprawling on the polished floor before him. It is not pleasant to come upon Death in a lonely place at midnight.</> - The God in the Bowl\n\nWithout bolts, a crossbow is just a really poorly shaped club.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51192_ShortDesc", "One-handed short spear that can be jabbed or thrown")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51192_LongDesc", "<span style="italic"> As they swept past the black mouth of a gorge that opened into the Pass, a javelin swished through the air and thudded home behind the stallion's straining shoulder.</> - The People of the Black Circle

The javelin is one of the most versatile weapons of the Hyborian age. Light weight enough to be wielded with a shield, the javelin is a common front line weapon in battles. 

Push, stab, push, stab is a motto of infantry the world over.

In addition, the javelin is light enough to be thrown with some degree of accuracy. Enemies fleeing a battle are almost always surprised to find three feet of spear jutting from between their shoulder blades.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51471_ShortDesc", "An arrow formed from ivory ")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51471_LongDesc", "Like cultures and customs, the value of ivory depends upon the kingdom where it is seen.

In the Hyborian kingdoms, where elephants and other creatures are rare, it is a tangible sign of both wealth and power. In the Black Kingdoms, it is common - few warriors exist in those lands who do not possess an ivory handled dagger or jewelry.

It is a great source of trade between the north and the south - indeed it could be said that ivory is the primary reason that merchants dare make the dangerous journey along the Black Coast to trade for it in Kush.

This ivory arrow, honed to perfection, is excellently balanced and will cause great damage.

Arrows can be equipped by dragging them over the bow in the inventory.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51472_ShortDesc", "A bolt formed from ivory")
column4:

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51503_ShortDesc", "Arrows tipped with sharp, black glass")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51503_LongDesc", "Forged in the depths of the Volcano that looms over the Exiled Lands, these arrows are made of obsidian. They are brittle, but the sharp facets of the black glass will cause additional damage to opponents.\n\nArrows can be equipped by dragging them over the bow in the inventory.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51504_ShortDesc", "Bolts tipped with sharp, black glass")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51504_LongDesc", "Forged in the depths of the Volcano that looms over the Exiled Lands, these bolts are made of obsidian. They are brittle, but the sharp facets of the black glass will cause additional damage to opponents.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51529_ShortDesc", "An arrow made in a blasphemous ancient style")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51529_LongDesc", "<span style="italic">And at last mankind conquered, so long ago that naught but dim legends come to us through the ages. The snake-people were the last to go, yet at last men conquered even them and drove them forth into the waste lands of the world, there to mate with true snakes until some day, say the sages, the horrid breed shall vanish utterly.</> - The Shadow Kingdom

The snake-people were thought to be gone. First defeated in the war with first man at the dawn of time, then purged again by King Kull of Valusia.

But here, in this bizarre, mysterious piece of the world, they found succor with the Giant-kings. Perhaps the city in the volcano was ancient before even the Giant-kings lived in this land. But either way, the degenerate remnant remains.

Arrows can be equipped by dragging them over the bow in the inventory.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51912_ShortDesc", "A light axe balanced for throwing")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51912_LongDesc", "<span style="italic"> And it was suspicious. It lifted its head, its eyes glowing like balls of fire, and growled low in its throat. And at that instant Conan hurled the axe. </> - Beyond the Black River

The Vanir raiders who plague the lands of the Cimmerians and Aesir often carry these light axes on their belts during their raids.

Held in the off-hand, these axes can be used for hacking at enemy shields and, in an emergency, hurled at their faces.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51922_ShortDesc", "A short spear of the Darfari style")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51922_LongDesc", "<span style="italic"> Black men came up the river in long boats with skulls grinning on the prows, or stole stooping through the trees, spear in hand.</> - Queen of the Black Coast

Adorned with feathers and tipped with flint, this short spear represents the pinnacle of Darfari weapons.

The Darfari use these spears for hunting game, first pinning their prey with well-aimed throws and then harassing their prey with swift, sharp stabs.

The feathers on the shaft are taken from the ferocious, but colourful, elephant birds that roam the grasslands on the very edges of Darfar.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51933_ShortDesc", "A hardened steel axe balanced for throwing")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51933_LongDesc", "<span style="italic">It wheeled at the thud of her soft boots on the floor, but even as it turned, her keen blade lashed down, and a fierce exultation swept her as she felt the edge cleave solid flesh and mortal bone.</> - Red Nails

Hardened steel, finely wrought, forms the head of this throwing axe and bears the swirling markings of a Cimmerian clan.

Held in the off-hand, these axes can be used for hacking at enemy shields and, in an emergency, hurled at their faces.

Cimmerians may be called savages and barbarians, but their understanding of metal smithing is relatively advanced. They know the riddle of steel, how to harden it for greater durability and vicious wounds.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51938_ShortDesc", "An axe forged from star metal and balanced for throwing")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51938_LongDesc", "<span style="italic">I am a queen by fire and steel and slaughter...</> - Queen of the Black Coast

This impossibly sharp throwing axe is made of legendary star metal, the work of a master craftsman.

Held in the off-hand, these axes can be used for hacking at enemy shields and, in an emergency, hurled at their faces.

Star metal is rare, smelted from ore that falls from the heavens. Weapons made from such material are preternaturally powerful.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51971_ShortDesc", "A glass orb that shimmers with fire")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51971_LongDesc", "<span style="italic">'His hand dipped into his robe and came out with something shining-a glistening sphere. This he threw suddenly at Conan. The Cimmerian contemptuously struck it aside with his sword-at the instant of contact there was a sharp explosion, a flare of white, blinding flame, and Conan pitched senseless to the ground.'</> - The Hour of the Dragon

While there are always rumors of sorcerers who summon fire from the skies and cause the earth to revolt against their foes, this orb is simply a concoction created from mixing fluids together.

To the credulous and superstitious, it appears to be sorcery. But to the educated it is simply an alchemical curiosity, able to set a burning fire on whatever surface it impacts.

It can also be used in combination with grease to create a larger fire effect.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51972_ShortDesc", "A glass orb filled with a greasy substance")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51972_LongDesc", "An orb filled with treated tar that leaves the tar slick and greasey. Upon application to a surface, this reduces friction and sudden changes of direction become impossible.\n\nThe grease can also be set alight by fire, or used to enhance the heat of a fire already burning.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51973_ShortDesc", "A glass orb filled with water")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51973_LongDesc", "<span style=\"italic\">\'There is a crystal jar on that ivory table,\' he answered. \'Fill it with water and tie a strip of that torn hanging about its neck for a handle while I rip up this tapestry.\'</> - Xuthal of the Dusk\n\nThis is simply a glass flask filled with water. It can be used to douse fires and to settle particles from the air. ")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51974_ShortDesc", "A glass orb filled with green gas")
column4:
NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_51974_LongDesc", "<span style="italic">'With sudden suspicion he thrust his head over the threshold, into the bluish mist that filled the inner cavern. And he screamed, chokingly: 'There is death in the smoke!'</> - The Black Stranger

This orb, filled with the spores of the pufferball mushroom, explodes into a cloud of green mist when thrown.

While the spores of the mushroom are not as potent as the pollen of the lotus or dust from Stygian tombs, they still cause significant damage to those unlucky enough to inhale them.

When combined with water, the spores also form a thick viscous substance that acts like grease. When a cloud of spores is met with fire, the resulting explosion rocks the very heavens.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_52896_ShortDesc", "A basic padding for use when crafting armors")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_52896_LongDesc", "Armor protects the body, but it can harm the body without the proper padding. This cushioned layer goes between the wearer and the actual armor.")

column3: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_53001_ShortDesc", "Extract of the aloe plant")
column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_53001_LongDesc", "Stygian traditions of healing hold that the aloe plant contains many desirable properties. In Luxur, the aloe is harvested for use in the temples of Derketo to cleanse blemishes from the skin of the priestesses. It is often used to sooth oozing wounds and those who ingest it claim that they feel a burst of wellbeing. Whether these effects are of the body or the mind is irrelevant - ingesting aloe extract seems to give the imbiber a regenerative health effect.")

column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_53002_LongDesc", "Stygian traditions of healing hold that the aloe plant contains many desirable properties. Whether these effects are of the body or the mind is irrelevant - ingesting aloe extract seems to give the imbiber a regenerative health effect.")

column4: NSLOCTEXT("", "ItemTable_53003_LongDesc", "Stygian traditions of healing hold that the aloe plant contains many desirable properties.
